Definition
 → z-index controls the stacking order of elements.
 → Higher z-index value appears on top.
 → Lower value appears behind.
Important Rule:
z-index works only on positioned elements.
(position: relative, absolute, fixed, sticky)
It does NOT work with: position: static;
Example of z-index
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
 <title>Z-Index Example</title>

 <style>
   .box1 {
     height: 200px;
     width: 300px;
     background-color: red;
     position: absolute;
     left: 100px;
     top: 100px;
     z-index: 1;
   }

   .box2 {
     height: 200px;
     width: 300px;
     background-color: blue;
     position: absolute;
     left: 150px;
     top: 150px;
     z-index: 2;
   }
 </style>
</head>

<body>

 <div class="box1"></div>
 <div class="box2"></div>

</body>
</html>

What Happens Here?
→ Blue box has z-index: 2
→ Red box has z-index: 1
→ Blue appears on top
Because 2 > 1
